SIMPLE: megrim
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Megrim
<hw>Me"grim</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>migrim</ets>, <ets>migrene</ets>, F. <ets>migraine</ets>, LL.
<ets>hemigrania</ets>, L. <ets>hemicrania</ets>, <ets>hemicranium</ets>,
Gr. <?/; <?/- half + <?/ skull. See <er>Hemi-</er> and <er>Cranium</er>,
and cf. <er>Hemicrania</er>, <er>Migraine</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A kind of sick or nervous headache, usually periodical and confined
to one side of the head; now more commonly called <altname>migraine
headache</altname> or <altname>migraine</altname>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A fancy; a whim; a freak; a humor; esp., in the
plural, lowness of spirits.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These are his <qex>megrims</qex>, firks, and melancholies.</q>
<rj><qau>Ford.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(Far.)</fld> <def>A sudden vertigo
in a horse, succeeded sometimes by unconsciousness, produced by an
excess of blood in the brain; a mild form of apoplexy.</def>
<rj><au>Youatt.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Megrim</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Megrim
<hw>Me"grim</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Etymol. uncertain.]</ety>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The British smooth sole, or scaldfish
(<spn>Psetta arnoglossa</spn>).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Meibomian</ent>⟦br⟧
